Encouraged by the excellent performance of these matrices in hosting various organic phosphors and boosting their RTP, we continued to develop a unique double-doped phase, namely (H2NAIP + (1, 4-NA))/1⋅Cl, by facilely embedding the two phosphors into 1⋅Cl simultaneously. Interestingly, this new phase has multi-emissions composed of dual fluorescence and dual RTP emission in the air at RT. A series of starting mole ratios were employed to adjust the emission intensities (Fig. 3
                        ). When the ratio of Al3+: (1, 4-NA): H2NAIP is 100: 1: 0.1, the obtained phase is WLE with its CIE coordinates being (0.34, 0.32) under 365 nm illumination. The characteristic RTP emissions of the two phosphors in the (H2NAIP + (1, 4-NA))/1⋅Cl are independent of the excitation wavelengths (Fig. 4
                         and S29).
